qas.question: What are the districts of Germany considered?
Every state, other than the free states, consist of districts called what?
How many urban districts are in Bremen?
Berlin and Hamburg are states and what else at the same time?
What districts do every state, including, Berlin, Hamburg and Bremen have?
What are towns and cities with districts called?
What are Berlin and Humburg not considered to be, because they are states?
How many rural districts are in Bremen?
Every state including free states consist of what?

context: The Districts of Germany (Kreise) are <a0_0>administrative districts<a0_0/>, and every state except the city-states of Berlin, Hamburg, and Bremen consists of <a1_0>"<b4_0><b8_0>rural districts<b8_0/><b4_0/>"<a1_0/> (Landkreise), District-free Towns/Cities (Kreisfreie Städte, in Baden-Württemberg also called "<b5_0>urban districts<b5_0/>", or Stadtkreise), cities that are districts in their own right, or local associations of a special kind (Kommunalverbände besonderer Art), see below. The state Free Hanseatic City of Bremen consists of <a2_0><b7_0>two<b7_0/><a2_0/> urban districts, while Berlin and Hamburg are states and <a3_0><b6_0>urban districts<b6_0/><a3_0/> at the same time.
